WEBVTT

00:00:00.160 --> 00:00:04.970
The application can also provide temporal variations of astronomical parameters

00:00:05.180 --> 00:00:07.230
and insolation series.

00:00:07.230 --> 00:00:10.310
To do so, let’s choose ' Create ' and then

00:00:10.310 --> 00:00:12.910
' Insolation / Astronomical series '.

00:00:14.030 --> 00:00:17.530
In the Type field, we can choose between various astronomical

00:00:17.530 --> 00:00:20.810
parameters and different types of insolation.

00:00:20.810 --> 00:00:24.140
We can then select the astronomical solution to use, with

00:00:24.140 --> 00:00:26.340
the reference shown on the right-hand side.

00:00:28.570 --> 00:00:31.300
We select the time period over which the series is

00:00:31.300 --> 00:00:32.580
computed.

00:00:32.580 --> 00:00:36.110
Past ages can be entered as negative or positive values

00:00:36.460 --> 00:00:39.770
We can choose the time unit: years or thousands of

00:00:39.770 --> 00:00:42.680
years, noted k y r in the interface.

00:00:43.980 --> 00:00:47.860
First, we plot the daily insolation using the ' Laskar

00:00:47.860 --> 00:00:50.830
2 0 04 ' astronomical solution.

00:00:50.830 --> 00:00:55.290
To represent Northern Hemisphere summer solstice insolation at 6 5

00:00:55.290 --> 00:00:59.680
North, we enter 65 in the latitude field and 90

00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:01.270
in the true longitude field.

00:01:03.570 --> 00:01:06.830
We can, for example, plot this insolation over the last

00:01:06.830 --> 00:01:10.220
1 6 0 thousand years, with a step of 0

00:01:10.220 --> 00:01:11.540
2.

00:01:11.540 --> 00:01:14.760
Please note that the application relies on true longitudes and

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:16.260
not calendar dates.

00:01:16.260 --> 00:01:19.280
The true longitude is illustrated in the schematic on the

00:01:19.280 --> 00:01:23.030
right-hand side: it corresponds to the angle ' lambda '

00:01:23.030 --> 00:01:26.590
between the vernal point ' gamma ', defined as 0

00:01:26.590 --> 00:01:28.770
°, and the position of the Sun as seen from

00:01:28.770 --> 00:01:30.090
Earth at a given time.

00:01:31.380 --> 00:01:35.010
The reason for using true longitudes instead of dates is

00:01:35.010 --> 00:01:39.610
illustrated in the second figure, accessible using the carousel navigation

00:01:39.610 --> 00:01:43.800
arrows: the length of the seasons, defined by fixed true-longitude

00:01:43.800 --> 00:01:46.020
intervals, varies through time.

00:01:46.020 --> 00:01:48.870
This is ignored when using fixed dates such as June

00:01:48.870 --> 00:01:49.610
21.

00:01:51.010 --> 00:01:54.280
In our case study, we also plot the daily insolation

00:01:54.280 --> 00:01:56.900
at a latitude of 5 ° South for the Southern

00:01:56.900 --> 00:02:00.710
Hemisphere summer solstice, still over the last 1 6 0

00:02:00.710 --> 00:02:02.280
thousand years.

00:02:02.280 --> 00:02:05.320
We then enter - 5 in the latitude field and

00:02:05.320 --> 00:02:08.320
2 7 0 in the true longitude field.

00:02:10.500 --> 00:02:12.660
We can click on ' Import series ' to save

00:02:12.660 --> 00:02:14.490
the insolation time series.

00:02:14.790 --> 00:02:19.170
Finally, we calculate and plot the integrated insolation between two

00:02:19.170 --> 00:02:22.110
true longitudes, selected in the Type field.

00:02:23.210 --> 00:02:26.690
We plot the insolation integrated over the Southern Hemisphere summer

00:02:26.690 --> 00:02:31.670
period, namely December, January, and February.

00:02:32.960 --> 00:02:36.820
We need to determine the corresponding true longitude values.

00:02:36.820 --> 00:02:39.510
We know that the true longitude of the Southern Hemisphere

00:02:39.510 --> 00:02:43.050
summer solstice is 2 7 0 °.

00:02:43.050 --> 00:02:46.250
We assume that 3 6 0 days correspond to 3

00:02:46.250 --> 00:02:48.820
6 0 ° of longitude.

00:02:48.820 --> 00:02:52.450
The Southern Hemisphere summer period, from early December to late

00:02:52.450 --> 00:02:57.170
February, roughly corresponds to true longitudes between 2 50 and

00:02:57.170 --> 00:03:00.060
3 4 0.

00:03:00.060 --> 00:03:03.550
We enter these values in True Longitude 1 and True

00:03:03.550 --> 00:03:04.750
Longitude 2.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:09.230
We click on ' Import series ' to save this

00:03:09.230 --> 00:03:12.500
Southern Hemisphere integrated summer insolation.

00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:14.660
Take a moment to name the series.

00:03:19.120 --> 00:03:22.210
We can now compare our filtered ' PercAndes ' record

00:03:22.510 --> 00:03:26.310
with this Southern Hemisphere integrated summer insolation curve.

00:03:28.770 --> 00:03:31.080
We click on ' Display Together ' and use a

00:03:31.080 --> 00:03:32.900
separate vertical axis.

00:03:34.970 --> 00:03:38.270
We observe that high values of the filtered ' PercAndes

00:03:38.270 --> 00:03:42.000
' record generally correspond to high insolation values.

00:03:43.150 --> 00:03:47.530
The scientific interpretation is that Southern Hemisphere integrated summer insolation

00:03:47.530 --> 00:03:52.320
controls, on precessional time scales, the intensity of the South

00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:56.750
American summer monsoon system, and thus the delivery of Andean-derived

00:03:56.750 --> 00:03:59.110
terrigenous material at the core site.
